      "text": "With a somewhat strange twist, Luhmann formulates that \"communication [is] realized when and insofar as understanding comes about.\" This sounds like a conclusion that is hard to imagine in an autopoietic time, especially since any utterance that follows an utterance will have been understanding only if a next utterance takes it up as a message/utterance of information.\n\n\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "77c1cc4a93c1e3f2",
      "text": "However, we do not take this diversion here, but stick to the point of view of 'realization': communication takes place at all only if information and utterance are distinguished at utterances by following utterances, i.e. their how (utterance) and their what (information) is treated as difference. This presupposes that participating mental systems can master this difference, for example, of which Lichtenberg speaks:\n\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "7dafdb1001f0a522",
      "text": "\"To understand the true meaning of a word in our mother tongue we certainly often spend many years. I also understand at the same time the meanings that the sound can give to it. The understanding of a word is given to us, to express myself mathematically, by a formula in which the sound is the variable and the word the constant quantity. Here opens a way to enrich the languages infinitely without increasing the words. I have found that the saying: It is good is pronounced by us in five different ways, and each time with a different meaning, which, of course, is also often determined by a third variable quantity, namely the mien.\"\n\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "c7c0294e52f1477a",
      "text": "If psychic systems cannot read that 'how' of utterances, they miss, in the most accurate understanding, the meaning of communication, the aspect of its rhetoric, any irony, the meaning of raising eyebrows, lowering volume, pauses, looking away, signs of anger, expressions of individuality ... The information is de-contextualized. As a case study of this, the autistic syndrome can be discussed, but also all disorders in which mental systems fail to interconnect through to (durchzuschließen) the self-reference of the people who produce utterances."
