    {
      "type": "add",
      "id": "77c1cc4a93c1e3f2",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "77c1cc4a93c1e3f2",
        "text": "However, we do not take this diversion here, but stick to the point of view of 'realization': communication takes place at all only if information and communication are distinguished at utterances by following utterances, i.e. their how (communication) and their what (information) is treated as difference. This presupposes that participating mental systems can master this difference, for example, of which Lichtenberg speaks:\n\n\"To understand the true meaning of a word in our mother tongue we certainly often spend many years. I also understand at the same time the meanings that the sound can give to it. The understanding of a word is given to us, to express myself mathematically, by a formula in which the sound is the variable and the word the constant quantity. Here opens a way to enrich the languages infinitely without increasing the words. I have found that the saying: It is good is pronounced by us in five different ways, and each time with a different meaning, which, of course, is also often determined by a third variable quantity, namely the mien.\"\n\nIf psychic systems cannot read that 'how' of utterances, they miss, in the most accurate understanding, the meaning of communication, the aspect of its rhetoric, any irony, the meaning of raising eyebrows, lowering volume, pauses, looking away, signs of anger, expressions of individuality ... The information is de-contextualized. As a case study of this, the autistic syndrome can be discussed3, but also all disorders in which mental systems fail to penetrate to the self-reference of the people who produce utterances."
